Let $\mathbf{a}' = \overrightarrow{A'},$ and define $\mathbf{b}' = \overrightarrow{B'},$ $\mathbf{c}' = \overrightarrow{C'},$ and $\mathbf{d}' = \overrightarrow{D'}.$  Then $\mathbf{a}' - \mathbf{b}' = \overrightarrow{BA},$ $\mathbf{c}' - \mathbf{b}' = \overrightarrow{BC},$ and $\mathbf{d}' - \mathbf{c}' = \overrightarrow{CD},$ so
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{b} &= \mathbf{a}' - \mathbf{b}' + \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}' \\
&= \mathbf{a}' - \mathbf{b}' + \mathbf{c}' - \mathbf{b}' + \mathbf{d}' - \mathbf{c}' + \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}' \\
&= (\mathbf{a}' + \mathbf{c}' + \mathbf{d}' - 3 \mathbf{b}') + (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}').
\end{align*}Hence, we can take
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} &= \mathbf{a}' + \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}'), \\
\mathbf{b} &= \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{a}' + \mathbf{b}' + \mathbf{c}' - \mathbf{d}'), \\
\mathbf{c} &= \mathbf{c}' + \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{d}' - \mathbf{c}'), \\
\mathbf{d} &= \frac{1}{3} (-\mathbf{a}' + \mathbf{b}' + \mathbf{c}' + \mathbf{d}').
\end{align*}Then
\[\overrightarrow{A} = \mathbf{a}' + \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}'),\]so $(p,q,r,s) = \boxed{\left( 1 + \frac{1}{3}, -\frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{3} \right)}.$

